46–before 1120","1038–1085":"1038–1085","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1042–Male":"1042–Deceased","1044–Male":"1044–Deceased","1046–1120":"1046–1120","1070–Female":"1070–Deceased","1090–1185":"1090–1185","1089–Male":"1089–Deceased","0995–Male":"0995–Deceased","1019–Female":"1019–Deceased","1091":"1091","1090":"1090","1044":"1044","1120":"1120","1185":"1185","1042":"1042","1085":"1085","1040":"1040","1070":"1070","1019":"1019","BEF 1120":"before 1120","0995":"0995","1038":"1038","1046":"1046","1089":"1089","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Brittany, Morbihan, France":"Morbihan, Brittany, France","Perrot, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Prute","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Wilhelm.","German: variant of <b>Prüter</b> (see   Prueter  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Prueter","meanings":["North German (<b>Prüter</b>):","perhaps from a personal name formed with a cognate of Old English <i>prūt</i> ‘proud’.","alternatively a nickname denoting a sloppy worker (used today in Schleswig-Holstein)."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Simon  , now rare, but more common in the Middle Ages, when it gave rise to the surnames <i>Simms</i> and <i>Simpson</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Simon","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"Perout","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse, Antoine, Philippe, Remy.","French (<b>Pérot</b>): from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Perre</i>, a variant of   Pierre  , French form of   Peter  . Compare   Perrow  .","Altered form of French   Perret  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Pierre","meanings":["From New Testament Greek.  See  <b>Peter</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Proute","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Prowse  .","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Preuss  .","Americanized form of German   Brause   2, a nickname for a violent, stormy person, from Middle High German <i>brūs</i> ‘noise, storm’."],"variants":[{"name":"Prowse","meanings":["English (Devon and Cornwall): nickname from Middle English <i>prous</i>, <i>prus</i>, variant forms of <i>prou</i> ‘brave, valiant, proud’ (see   Prue  ).","English (Devon and Cornwall): ethnic name: from Middle English <i>Prus(se)</i>, <i>Pruce</i> ‘Prussia, Prussian’, for someone from that region. Compare   Sprouse  .","Americanized form of German   Prause   or   Praus  , or perhaps of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Jean Perout Proute Prute was born in 1046, in Morbihan, Brittany, France, his father, Sir Richard Seignuer De Perrot, was 51 and his mother, Blanche de Aragon, was 27. He married Marged Verch Cadivor Vawr in 1091, in Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 1120, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1046–BEF 1120":"1046–enne 1120","1038–1085":"1038–1085","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1042–Male":"1042–Surnud","1044–Male":"1044–Surnud","1046–1120":"1046–1120","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","1090–1185":"1090–1185","1089–Male":"1089–Surnud","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","1019–Female":"1019–Surnud","1091":"1091","1090":"1090","1044":"1044","1120":"1120","1185":"1185","1042":"1042","1085":"1085","1040":"1040","1070":"1070","1019":"1019","BEF 1120":"enne 1120","0995":"0995","1038":"1038","1046":"1046","1089":"1089","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brittany, Morbihan, France":"Morbihan, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Perrot, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1046–BEF 1120":"1046–ennen vuotta 1120","1038–1085":"1038–1085","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1042–Male":"1042–Kuollut","1044–Male":"1044–Kuollut","1046–1120":"1046–1120","1070–Female":"1070–Kuollut","1090–1185":"1090–1185","1089–Male":"1089–Kuollut","0995–Male":"0995–Kuollut","1019–Female":"1019–Kuollut","1091":"1091","1090":"1090","1044":"1044","1120":"1120","1185":"1185","1042":"10